  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 G6PD: Oxidizers out, antioxidants in!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies pharmacologic agents that induce hemolytic anemia in patients with Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency. This condition renders erythrocytes susceptible to oxidative stress, leading to hemolysis upon exposure to specific drugs or chemicals.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nG6PD is a critical enzyme in the pentose phosphate pathway, responsible for producing NADPH, which is essential for reducing glutathione. Reduced glutathione protects red blood cells from oxidative damage. In G6PD deficiency, insufficient NADPH levels make erythrocytes vulnerable to oxidative stress. Drugs such as acetylsalicylic acid (at high doses), sulfamethoxazole, and nitrofurantoin are oxidizing agents that generate reactive oxygen species, overwhelming the compromised antioxidant defenses in G6PD-deficient red blood cells. This leads to hemoglobin denaturation, formation of Heinz bodies, and subsequent extravascular hemolysis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption b (Vitamin E) (Incorrect): Vitamin E is a potent antioxidant and is considered therapeutic for G6PD deficient patients, as it helps protect red blood cells from oxidative damage, rather than inducing it.\nOption d (Desferrioxamine) (Incorrect): Desferrioxamine is an iron chelator with antioxidant properties. It is also considered therapeutic for G6PD deficient patients, likely due to its antioxidant effects, and does not induce hemolysis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Category | Examples | Mechanism/Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Hemolysis Inducers** | Acetylsalicylic acid (high dose), Sulfamethoxazole, Nitrofurantoin, Primaquine, Fava beans | Oxidizing agents that generate reactive oxygen species, overwhelming G6PD-deficient RBCs |\n| **Therapeutic Agents** | Vitamin E, Desferrioxamine | Antioxidants that help protect RBCs from oxidative damage |\n| **G6PD Deficiency** | X-linked recessive disorder | Impaired NADPH production, leading to susceptibility to oxidative stress and hemolytic anemia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Avoid oxidizing agents in G6PD deficiency to prevent hemolysis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn acute hemolytic anemia, patients may present with jaundice, pallor, and dark urine. Splenomegaly might be observed on imaging or physical exam due to increased red blood cell destruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2020 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Glucose-6-Phosphate Dehydrogenase Deficiency recommend avoiding known oxidative stressors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Acetylsalicylic acid | ✅ Correct |\n| b | Vitamin E | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Sulfamethoxazole | ✅ Correct |\n| d | Desferrioxamine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| e | Nitrofurantoin | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, c, e) Generally, G6PD deficiency is not clinically apparent; hemolytic anemia occurs in most patients only** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 385387853-medcosmossurgery-blogspot-in-20-pdf.pdf**\n",
